\Title {Data-Driven Penetration Prediction and Probabilistic Impingement Screening from Mie-Scattering Videos}
\Author {Linan Jiang}
\Language {en}
\Copyright {\textcopyright \ 2026. This work is licensed under a Creative Commons "Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International" (BY-NC-SA 4.0) license.}
\CopyrightURL {https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/deed.en}
\Subject {Pilot diesel injections in multi-fuel marine engines are short, strongly transient events. If the liquid envelope reaches the piston crown or cylinder wall before useful ignition develops, wall wetting, lubricant dilution, and poor mixture preparation can follow. This thesis develops an evidence-grounded screening workflow that converts high-speed Mie-scattering videos into penetration-oriented observables and a surrogate model for early spray-wall-risk assessment. The data consist of room-temperature, non-reacting top-view recordings from the W\"artsil\"a Optical Spray Combustion Chamber, covering multiple operating conditions and nozzle geometries. The workflow combines manual nozzle calibration, CUDA-accelerated multihole video processing, plume-wise feature extraction, and a reduced-order trajectory fit that both smooths noisy labels and reduces the downward bias caused by right-censored observations near the field-of-view limit. On these fitted targets, a three-stage neural surrogate is trained. Stage 1 learns a deterministic representative-trajectory baseline. Stage 2 extends the model to heteroscedastic mean-and-variance prediction on the full filtered dataset. Stage 3 refines early-time behaviour against raw CDF observations while retaining conservative teacher guidance where late-time coverage becomes sparse. This staging is designed to prevent the model from mistaking disappearance from the image window for physical saturation. On 692,942 held-out prediction points from 24,316 trajectories across 9 nozzle campaigns under the full-clean CDF evaluation protocol, the final anchor-off Stage 3 model with mse-mu-plus-sigma distillation achieves a five-seed mean RMSE of 4.74 mm and MAE of 3.29 mm, with a seed-to-seed standard deviation below 0.04 mm, while retaining 86.7 percent at 1 sigma and 98.5 percent at 2 sigma uncertainty coverage. Compared with calibrated Hiroyasu--Arai and delayed Naber--Siebers empirical baselines, the model reduces RMSE by more than 55 percent; the sparse heteroscedastic Gaussian-process alternative backbone achieves slightly lower point error at 4.63 mm RMSE but with substantially lower uncertainty coverage. A simplified geometric projection then maps the predicted penetration distribution onto a probabilistic collision-screening proxy. The intended use is explicit: the workflow is an early-stage engineering screening tool within its measured operating domain, not a substitute for CFD, engine testing, or validated in-cylinder impingement physics.}
\Keywords {Mie scattering\sep spray imaging\sep penetration\sep computer vision\sep surrogate modeling}
